# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dodge-coronet
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dodge-coronet/1955-dodge] The **1955 Dodge** car lineup, consisting of the entry-level Coronet, Royal, and ornate Custom Royal, was a major departure for the company.
[src:dodge-coronet/1955-dodge] Driven almost out of business in 1953 and 1954, the Chrysler Corporation was revived with a $250 million loan from Prudential and new models designed by Virgil Exner.
[src:dodge-coronet/1955-dodge] The Dodge lineup was positioned as the mainstream line in Chrysler's hierarchy, between DeSoto and Plymouth.
[src:dodge-coronet/1955-dodge] The 1955 Dodge was all-new with a 120 in (3048 mm) wheelbase and 212.1 in (5387 mm) overall length, longer than the 1954 cars.
[src:dodge-coronet/1955-dodge] They shared their basic mechanicals with the DeSoto Custom, but had distinct styling.
[src:dodge-coronet/1955-dodge] These cars lasted through the 1956 model year before being replaced by an all-new 1957.
[src:dodge-coronet/1955-dodge] The **Coronet** (and **Suburban** station wagon) was the base model.
[src:dodge-coronet/1955-dodge] This was the only line to feature the 230 in3 (3.8 L) *Getaway* I6 as well as the 270 in3 (4.4 L) *Red Ram* V8.
[src:dodge-coronet/1955-dodge] Coronets were available in all body styles except the convertible.
[src:dodge-coronet/1955-dodge] Sedans feature "Coronet" badges on the fenders, while the station wagons are called "Suburban".
[src:dodge-coronet/1955-dodge] Although the hardtop coupe was officially named "Lancer", it wore only "Coronet" badges.
[src:dodge-coronet/1955-dodge] Turn signals were standard on the Royal and Custom Royal models but optional on the base Coronet.
[src:dodge-coronet/1955-dodge] The **Royal** (and **Sierra** wagon) were the next step up.
[src:dodge-coronet/1955-dodge] Featuring only the V8 engine, the Royal also lacked the 2-door sedan and wagon models available in the Coronet line.
[src:dodge-coronet/1955-dodge] Early hardtop coupes lack the "Lancer" script, although they were officially Lancers, but later models wore "Royal Lancer" badges.
[src:dodge-coronet/1955-dodge] The flagship model was the **Custom Royal**.
[src:dodge-coronet/1955-dodge] All hardtop coupe and Custom Royal-only convertible models were called "Custom Royal Lancer".
[src:dodge-coronet/1955-dodge] The Custom line featured unique chrome tailfins (although early model year cars went without this trim), special tail light surrounds, and an upscale interior.
[src:dodge-coronet/1955-dodge] Backup lights were standard on the Custom line but optional on all others.
[src:dodge-coronet/1955-dodge] The Custom Royal also featured the hemi 270 CID Super Red Ram engine.
[src:dodge-coronet/1955-dodge] The **La Femme** was a special package oriented towards women, who made up an increasing share of Dodge buyers.
[src:dodge-coronet/1955-dodge] It came in Heather Rose and Sapphire White colors and included a cape, boots, umbrella, and shoulder bag that matched the floral tapestry-like fabrics.
[src:dodge-coronet/1955-dodge] Changes to the car include built-in compartments in the seatbacks to hold these accessories.
[src:dodge-coronet/1955-dodge] The 1956 **D-500** was a high-performance model derived from the standard 1956 Dodge but differing in many ways.
[src:dodge-coronet/1955-dodge] It included a heavy duty suspension and other chassis upgrades from the New Yorker and Imperial lines, upgraded brakes, and a high-performance 315 in3 (5.2 L) Hemi-head V8.
[src:dodge-coronet/1955-dodge] A four-barrel Carter carburetor pushed output to 260 hp (194 kW) and 330 lb·ft (447 N·m).
[src:dodge-coronet/1955-dodge] The 3-speed manual transmission was standard, with the PowerFlite 2-speed automatic as an option.
[src:dodge-coronet/1955-dodge] A rare NASCAR-specific option was the D-500-1(Dash-1), which upped power to 285 hp (213 kW).
[src:dodge-coronet/1955-dodge] The D-500 originally used only the Coronet 2-door sedan and Royal Lancer hardtop and convertible bodies.
[src:dodge-coronet/1955-dodge] For the 1957 model year, Chrysler embarked on a second total linewide redesign.
[src:dodge-coronet/1955-dodge] Virgil Exner's "Forward Design" brought about cars that were bigger and more sleek than anything before, and instantly put a company that had traditionally regarded styling as unimportant on the forefront of automotive design.
[src:dodge-coronet/1955-dodge] Unfortunately, two total redesigns in as many years resulted in severe build quality and rust problems, so that many 1957 Chryslers, Dodges, and Plymouths were off the road within three years of their purchase.
[src:dodge-coronet/1955-dodge] While many of the quality issues were resolved for the 1958 model year, which brought about some minor styling tweaks, a recession struck that was particularly damaging to sales of mid-range cars.
[src:dodge-coronet/1955-dodge] Dodge production had exceeded 337,000 cars for 1957 but the 1958 total fell by over half to less than 140,000, although some of this loss was due to negative publicity from the cars' poor quality control.
[src:dodge-coronet/1955-dodge] 1959 Dodges were facelifted to gain a heavy, drooping look with hooded headlamps.
[src:dodge-coronet/1955-dodge] Production for the model year totaled 156,395 cars, a modest increase over 1958.
[src:dodge-coronet/1955-dodge] The highlight of the lineup was the performance-oriented D-500 package.
[src:dodge-coronet/1955-dodge] Power came from either a 230 cu in (4 L) flathead straight six or one of two 270 cu in (4 L) V8s.
[src:dodge-coronet/1955-dodge] The regular Red Ram V8 was standard on the Royal and optional on the Coronet.
[src:dodge-coronet/1955-dodge] A hemi V8 (the Super Red Ram) was standard on the Custom Royal.
[src:dodge-coronet/1955-dodge] A rare Power Pack was optional, consisting of a four-barrel Carter carburetor and dual exhausts good for 193 hp (144 kW; 196 PS) with the Hemi engine.
[src:dodge-coronet/1955-dodge] Two transmissions were offered: a three-speed manual with optional overdrive and Chrysler's two-speed PowerFlite automatic.
[src:dodge-coronet/1955-dodge] The PowerFlite was controlled by a dash-mounted lever, though this was changed to a push-button setup for 1956.
[src:dodge-coronet/1955-dodge] The cars used a special coil spring/kingpin suspension in front and regular leaf springs and a live axle at the rear.
[src:dodge-coronet/1955-dodge] A six-volt electrical system was updated to 12 volts in 1956.
[src:dodge-coronet/american-antiquarian-society] The **American Antiquarian Society** (**AAS**), located in Worcester, Massachusetts, is a learned society and a national research library of pre-twentieth-century American history and culture.
[src:dodge-coronet/american-antiquarian-society] Founded in 1812, it is the oldest historical society in the United States with a national focus.
[src:dodge-coronet/american-antiquarian-society] Its main building, known as Antiquarian Hall, is a U.S.
[src:dodge-coronet/american-antiquarian-society] National Historic Landmark in recognition of this legacy.
[src:dodge-coronet/american-antiquarian-society] The mission of the AAS is to collect, preserve and make available for study all printed records of what is now known as the United States of America.
[src:dodge-coronet/american-antiquarian-society] This includes materials from the first European settlement through the year 1900.
[src:dodge-coronet/american-antiquarian-society] The collections of the AAS contain over four million books, pamphlets, newspapers, periodicals, graphic arts materials and manuscripts.
[src:dodge-coronet/american-antiquarian-society] The Society is estimated to hold copies of two-thirds of the total books known to have been printed in what is now the United States from the establishment of the first press in 1640 through the year 1820; many of these volumes are exceedingly rare and a number of them are unique.
[src:dodge-coronet/american-antiquarian-society] Historic materials from all fifty U.S. states, most of Canada and the British West Indies are included in the AAS repository.
[src:dodge-coronet/american-antiquarian-society] An act of congress requires that one copy of the journals of the Senate and of the House of Representatives along with other documents are to be transmitted to the Governor of Massachusetts for the use and benefit of the Society.
[src:dodge-coronet/american-antiquarian-society] One of the more notable volumes held by the Society is a copy of the first book printed in America, the Bay Psalm Book.
[src:dodge-coronet/american-antiquarian-society] AAS has one of the largest collections of newspapers printed in America through 1876, with more than two million issues in its collection.
[src:dodge-coronet/american-antiquarian-society] On the initiative of Isaiah Thomas, the AAS was founded on October 24, 1812, through an act of the Massachusetts General Court.
[src:dodge-coronet/american-antiquarian-society] It was the third historical society established in America, and the first to be national in its scope.
[src:dodge-coronet/american-antiquarian-society] Isaiah Thomas started the collection with approximately 8,000 books from his personal library.
[src:dodge-coronet/american-antiquarian-society] The first library building was erected in 1820 in downtown Worcester, Massachusetts.
[src:dodge-coronet/american-antiquarian-society] In 1853, the Society moved its collections to a larger building at the corner of Highland Street, also in Worcester.
[src:dodge-coronet/american-antiquarian-society] This building was later abandoned and another new building was constructed.
[src:dodge-coronet/american-antiquarian-society] Designed by Winslow, Bigelow & Wadsworth, the Georgian Revival building was completed in 1910 and stands on the corner of Park Avenue and Salisbury Street.
[src:dodge-coronet/american-antiquarian-society] There have been several additions to this building to accommodate the growing collection.
[src:dodge-coronet/american-antiquarian-society] The most recent addition was completed in 2019 and created room for an updated HVAC system, conservation lab, and multi-use learning lab.
[src:dodge-coronet/american-antiquarian-society] AAS was presented with the 2013 National Humanities Medal by President Obama in a ceremony at the White House.
[src:dodge-coronet/american-antiquarian-society] As part of AAS's mission as a learned society, it offers a variety of public lectures and seminars.
[src:dodge-coronet/american-antiquarian-society] One topic to which AAS dedicates significant academic energies is printing technology, especially in 18th century British North America.
[src:dodge-coronet/american-antiquarian-society] Since Isaiah Thomas was a newspaper man himself, he collected a large number of printed materials.
[src:dodge-coronet/american-antiquarian-society] With regard to printing, paper making, edition setting, and reprinting, not much had changed in European technology by the eighteenth century.
[src:dodge-coronet/american-antiquarian-society] It was not until the late eighteenth century that paper-making material began to evolve from a hand-woven cloth to an industrial pulp.
[src:dodge-coronet/american-antiquarian-society] AAS undertakes special efforts to preserve printed records from this time period, as the Society maintains an on-site conservation department with various sewing, cloth, and binding materials to aid in the preservation process.
[src:dodge-coronet/american-antiquarian-society] Over its two-hundred-year history, the Society has had 14 formal leaders who have shaped the organization's vision, collections, and day-to-day operations.
[src:dodge-coronet/american-antiquarian-society] Leadership roles at the AAS have historically overlapped in chronology, as different roles oversaw different aspects of the Society simultaneously.
[src:dodge-coronet/american-antiquarian-society] The American Antiquarian Society's membership includes scholars, writers, journalists, historians, artists, filmmakers, collectors, American presidents, and civic leaders.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] An **automatic transmission** (**AT**) or **automatic gearbox** is a multi-speed transmission used in motor vehicles that does not require any input from the driver other than throttle position to change forward gears under normal driving conditions.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] The 1904 Sturtevant "horseless carriage gearbox" is often considered to be the first true automatic transmission.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] The first mass-produced automatic transmission was General Motors' Hydra-Matic, introduced in Oldsmobile models for the 1940 model year.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] Automatic transmissions are especially prevalent in vehicular drivetrains, particularly those subject to intense mechanical acceleration and frequent idle/transient operating conditions; commonly commercial/passenger/utility vehicles, such as buses and waste collection vehicles.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] Vehicles with internal combustion engines, unlike electric vehicles, require the engine to operate in a narrow range of rates of rotation, requiring a gearbox, operated manually or automatically, to drive the wheels over a wide range of speeds.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] Globally, 43% of new cars produced in 2015 were manual transmissions, falling to 37% by 2020.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] Automatic transmissions have long been prevalent in the United States, but only started to become common in Europe much later.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] In Europe in 1997, only 10–12% of cars had automatic transmissions.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] In 1957 over 80% of new cars in the United States had automatic transmissions.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] Automatic transmissions have been standard in large cars since at least 1974.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] By 2020 only 2.4% of new cars had manual transmissions.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] Historically, automatic transmissions were less efficient, but lower fuel prices in the US made this less of a problem than in Europe.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] In the United Kingdom, a majority of new cars have had automatic transmissions since 2020.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] Several manufacturers including Mercedes and Volvo no longer sell cars with manual transmissions.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] The growing prevalence of automatic transmissions is attributed to the increasing number of electric and hybrid cars, and the ease of integrating it with safety systems such as Autonomous Emergency Braking.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] The efficiency (power output as a percentage of input) of conventional automatic transmissions ranges from 86 to 94%.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] Manual transmissions are more fuel efficient than all but the newest automatic transmissions due to their inherently low parasitic losses (typically of about 4%) in addition to being cheaper to make, lighter, better performing, and of simpler mechanical design.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] Fuel economy worsens with lower efficiency.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] However, manual transmissions require the driver to operate the clutch and change gear whenever required.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] Real-world tests reported in 2022 found that in typical driving manual transmissions achieved 2 to 5% better fuel economy than automatics, increasing to 20% with an expert driver.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] Some laboratory tests show automatics in a better light due to the tests using a prescribed shifting pattern for manuals not always optimized for economy.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] However, on long highway journeys manual transmissions require maintaining a very specific cruising speed to optimise economy, making automatics preferable.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] The most common design of automatic transmissions is the hydraulic automatic, which typically uses planetary gearsets that are operated using hydraulics.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] The transmission is connected to the engine via a torque converter (or a fluid coupling prior to the 1960s), instead of the friction clutch used by most manual transmissions.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] A hydraulic automatic transmission uses planetary gearsets instead of the manual transmission's design of gears lined up along input, output and intermediate shafts.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] To change gears, the hydraulic automatic uses a combination of internal clutches, friction bands or brake packs.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] These devices are used to lock certain gears, thus setting which gear ratio is in use at a given time.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] A sprag clutch (a ratchet-like device which can freewheel and transmits torque in only one direction) is often used for routine gear shifts.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] The advantage of a sprag clutch is that it eliminates the sensitivity of timing a simultaneous clutch release/apply on two planetary gearsets, simply "taking up" the drivetrain load when actuated, and releasing automatically when the next gear's sprag clutch assumes the torque transfer.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] The friction bands are often used for manually selected gears (such as low range or reverse) and operate on the planetary drum's circumference.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] Bands are not applied when the drive/overdrive range is selected, the torque being transmitted by the sprag clutches instead.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] The aforementioned friction bands and clutches are controlled using automatic transmission fluid (ATF), which is pressurized by a pump and then directed to the appropriate bands/clutches to obtain the required gear ratio.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] The ATF provides lubrication, corrosion prevention, and a hydraulic medium to transmit the power required to operate the transmission.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] Made from petroleum with various refinements and additives, ATF is one of the few parts of the automatic transmission that needs routine service as the vehicle ages.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] The *main pump* which pressurises the ATF is typically a gear pump mounted between the torque converter and the planetary gear set.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] The input for the main pump is connected to the torque converter housing, which in turn is bolted to the engine's flexplate, so the pump provides pressure whenever the engine is running.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] The pressure of the ATF is regulated by a *governor* connected to the output shaft, which varies the pressure depending on the vehicle speed.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] The *valve body* inside the transmission is responsible for directing hydraulic pressure to the appropriate bands and clutches.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] It receives pressurized fluid from the main pump and consists of several spring-loaded valves, check balls, and servo pistons.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] In older automatic transmissions, the valves use the pump pressure and the pressure from a centrifugal governor on the output side (as well as other inputs, such as throttle position or the driver locking out the higher gears) to control which ratio is selected.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] As the vehicle and engine change speed, the difference between the pressures changes, causing different sets of valves to open and close.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] In more recent automatic transmissions, the valves are controlled by solenoids.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] These solenoids are computer-controlled, with the gear selection decided by a dedicated transmission control unit (TCU) or sometimes this function is integrated into the engine control unit (ECU).
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] Modern designs have replaced the centrifugal governor with an electronic speed sensor that is used as an input to the TCU or ECU.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] Modern transmissions also factor in the amount of load on an engine at any given time, which is determined from either the throttle position or the amount of intake manifold vacuum.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] The multitude of parts, along with the complex design of the valve body, originally made hydraulic automatic transmissions much more expensive and time-consuming to build and repair than manual transmissions; however mass-production and developments over time have reduced this cost gap.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] To provide coupling and decoupling of the engine, a modern automatic transmission uses a torque converter instead of the friction clutch used in a manual transmission.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] The 1904 Sturtevant "horseless carriage gearbox" is often considered to be the first automatic transmission for motor vehicles.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] At higher engine speeds, high gear was engaged.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] As the vehicle slowed down and engine speed decreased, the gearbox would shift back to low.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] However, the transmission was prone to sudden failure, due to the transmission being unable to withstand forces from the abrupt gear changes.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] The adoption of planetary gearsets was a significant advance towards the modern automatic transmission.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] One of the first transmissions to use this design was the manual transmission fitted to the 1901–1904 Wilson-Pilcher automobile.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] This transmission was built in the United Kingdom and used two epicyclic gears to provide four gear ratios.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] A foot clutch was used for standing starts, gear selection was using a hand lever, helical gears were used (to reduce noise) and the gears used a constant-mesh design.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] A planetary gearset was also used in the 1908 Ford Model T, which was fitted with a two-speed manual transmission (without helical gears).
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] An early patent for the automatic transmission was granted to Canadian inventor Alfred Horner Munro of Regina in 1923.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] Being a steam engineer, Munro designed his device to use compressed air rather than hydraulic fluid, and so it lacked power and never found commercial application.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] In 1923, a patent was approved in the United States describing the operation of a transmission where the manual shifting of gears and manual operation of a clutch was eliminated.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] Hoffman from Chicago and was titled: *Automatic Gear Shift and Speed Control*.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] However, it would be over a decade later until automatic transmissions were produced in significant quantities.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] In the meantime, several European and British manufacturers would use preselector gearboxes, a form of manual transmission which removed the reliance on the driver's skill to achieve smooth gear shifts.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] The first automatic transmission using hydraulic fluid was developed in 1932 by two Brazilian engineers, José Braz Araripe and Fernando Lehly Lemos.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] The evolution towards mass-produced automatic transmissions continued with the 1933–1935 REO Motor Car Company *Self-Shifter* semi-automatic transmission, which automatically shifted between two forward gears in the "Forward" mode (or between two shorter gear ratios in the "Emergency low" mode).
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] Driver involvement was still required during normal driving, since standing starts required the driver to use the clutch pedal.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] This was followed in 1937 by the Oldsmobile *Automatic Safety Transmission*.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] Similar in operation to the REO *Self-Shifter*, the *Automatic Safety Transmission* shifted automatically between the two gear ratios available in the "Low" and "High" ranges and the clutch pedal was required for standing starts.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] The Chrysler *Fluid Drive*, introduced in 1939, was an optional addition to manual transmissions where a fluid coupling (similar to a torque-convertor, but without the torque multiplication) was added, to avoid the need to operate a manual clutch.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] The General Motors Hydra-Matic became the first mass-produced automatic transmission following its introduction in 1939 (1940 model year).
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] Available as an option in cars such as the Oldsmobile Series 60 and Cadillac Sixty Special, the Hydra-Matic combined a fluid coupling with three hydraulically controlled planetary gearsets to produce four forward speeds plus reverse.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] The transmission was sensitive to engine throttle position and road speed, producing fully automatic up- and down-shifting that varied according to operating conditions.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] During World War II, the Hydra-Matic was used in some military vehicles.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] The first automatic transmission to use a torque converter (instead of a fluid coupling) was the Buick Dynaflow, which was introduced for the 1948 model year.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] In normal driving, the Dynaflow used only the top gear, relying on the torque multiplication of the torque convertor at lower speeds.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] The Dynaflow was followed by the Packard Ultramatic in mid-1949 and the Chevrolet Powerglide for the 1950 model year.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] Each of these transmissions had only two forward speeds, relying on the converter for additional torque multiplication.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] In the early 1950s, BorgWarner developed a series of three-speed torque converter automatics for car manufacturers such as American Motors, Ford and Studebaker.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] Chrysler was late in developing its own true automatic, introducing the two-speed torque converter PowerFlite in 1953, and the three-speed TorqueFlite in 1956.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] The latter was the first to utilize the Simpson compound planetary gearset.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] In 1956, the General Motors Hydra-Matic (which still used a fluid coupling) was redesigned based around the use of two fluid couplings to provide smoother shifts.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] This transmission was called the *Controlled Coupling Hydra-Matic*, or "Jetaway" transmission.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] The original Hydra-Matic remained in production until the mid-1960s at GM, with the licensed Rolls-Royce Automatic transmission soldiering on until 1978 on the Rolls-Royce Phantom VI.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] In 1964, General Motors released a new transmission, the Turbo Hydramatic, a three-speed transmission which used a torque convertor.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] The Turbo Hydramatic was among the first to have the basic gear selections (*park*, *reverse*, *neutral*, *drive*, *low*) which became the standard gear selection used for several decades.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] By the late 1960s, most of the fluid-coupling two-speed and four-speed transmissions had disappeared in favor of three-speed units with torque converters.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] Also around this time, whale oil was removed from the automatic transmission fluid.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] During the 1980s, automatic transmissions with four gear ratios became increasingly common, and many were equipped with lock-up torque convertors in order to improve fuel economy.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] Electronics began to be more commonly used to control the transmission, replacing mechanical control methods such as spring-loaded valves in the valve body.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] Most systems use solenoids which are controlled by either the engine control unit, or a separate transmission control unit.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] This allows for more precise control of shift points, shift quality, lower shift times and manual control.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] The first five-speed automatic was the Jatco 5R01, introduced in 1989 by Nissan in the Cedric and Gloria, and was electronically controlled.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] The first six-speed automatic was the ZF 6HP26 transmission, which debuted in the 2002 BMW 7 Series (E65).
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] The first seven-speed automatic was the Mercedes-Benz 7G-Tronic transmission, which debuted a year later.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] In 2007, the first eight-speed transmission to reach production was the Toyota AA80E transmission.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] The first nine-speed and ten-speed transmissions were the 2013 ZF 9HP transmission and 2017 *Toyota Direct Shift-10A* (used in the Lexus LC) respectively.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] The gear selector is the input by which the driver selects the operating mode of an automatic transmission.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] A few automobiles employed a lever on the instrument panel, such as the 1955 Chrysler Corporation cars, and notably, the Corvair.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] Some automatic transmissions, especially by General Motors from 1940 to 1964, used a layout with *reverse* as the bottom position (e.g.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] Many transmissions also include positions to restrict the gear selection to the lower gears and engages the engine brake.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] These positions are often labelled "L" (low gear), "S" (second gear) or the number of the highest gear used in that position (eg 3, 2 or 1).
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] If these positions are engaged at a time when it would result in excessive engine speed, many modern transmissions disregard the selector position and remain in the higher gear.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] Many modern transmissions include modes to adjust the shift logic to prefer either power or fuel economy.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] "Sport" (also called "Power" or "Performance") modes cause gear shifts to occur at higher engine speeds, allowing higher acceleration.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] "Economy" (also called "Eco" or "Comfort") modes cause gear shifts to occur at lower engine speeds to reduce fuel consumption.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] Since the 1990s, systems to manually request a specific gear or an upshift/downshift have become more common.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] These *manumatic* transmissions offer the driver greater control over the gear selection that the traditional modes to restrict the transmission to the lower gears.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] Use of the manumatic functions are typically achieved either via paddles located beside the steering column, or "+" and "-" controls on the gear selector.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] Some cars offer drivers both methods to request a manual gear selection.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] A *continuously variable transmission* (CVT) can change seamlessly through a continuous (infinite) range of gear ratios, compared with other automatic transmissions that provide a limited number of gear ratios in fixed steps.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] The flexibility of a CVT with suitable control may allow the engine to operate at a constant angular velocity while the vehicle moves at varying speeds.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] CVTs are used in cars, tractors, UTVs, motor scooters, snowmobiles, and earthmoving equipment.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] The most common type of CVT uses two pulleys connected by a belt or chain.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] However, several other designs have also been used.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] A *dual-clutch transmission* (DCT, sometimes referred to as a *twin-clutch transmission*, or *double-clutch transmission*) uses two separate clutches for odd and even gear sets.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] The design is often similar to two separate manual transmissions with their respective clutches contained within one housing, and working as one unit.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] In most car and truck applications, the DCT functions as an automatic transmission, requiring no driver input to change gears.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] The first DCT to reach production was the *Easidrive* automatic transmission introduced on the 1961 *Hillman Minx* mid-size car.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] This was followed by various eastern European tractors through the 1970s (using manual operation via a single clutch pedal), then the *Porsche 962 C* racing car in 1985.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] The first DCT of the modern era was used in the 2003 *Volkswagen Golf R32*.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] Since the late 2000s, DCTs have become increasingly widespread, and have supplanted hydraulic automatic transmissions in various models of cars.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] Modern versions of these systems that are fully automatic in operation, such as *Selespeed* and *Easytronic*, require no driver input over gear changes or clutch operation.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] Semi-automatic versions require only partial driver input (i.e., the driver must change gears manually), while fully automatic versions require no manual driver input, whatsoever (TCU or ECU operates both the clutch system and gear shifts automatically).
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] Modern automated manual transmissions (AMT) have their roots and origins in older clutchless manual transmissions that began to appear on mass-production automobiles in the early 1930s and 1940s, prior to the introduction of hydraulic automatic transmissions.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] These systems were designed to reduce the amount of clutch or gear shifter usage required by the driver.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] These devices were intended to reduce the difficulty of operating conventional unsynchronised manual transmissions ("crash gearboxes") that were commonly used at the time, especially in stop-start driving.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] An early example of this transmission was introduced with the Hudson Commodore in 1942, called *Drive-Master*.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] Another early example of this transmission system was introduced in the 1955 Citroën DS, which used a 4-speed *BVH* transmission.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] This semi-automatic transmission used an automated clutch, which was actuated using hydraulics.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] Gear selection also used hydraulics, however, the gear ratio needs to be manually selected by the driver.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] This system was nicknamed *Citro-Matic* in the U.S.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] The first modern AMTs were introduced by BMW and Ferrari in 1997, with their *SMG* and *F1* transmissions, respectively.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] Both systems used hydraulic actuators and electrical solenoids, and a designated transmission control unit (TCU) for the clutch and shifting, plus steering wheel-mounted paddle shifters, if the driver wanted to change gear manually.
[src:dodge-coronet/automatic-transmission] Modern fully automatic AMTs, such as *Selespeed* and *Easytronic*, have now been largely superseded and replaced by the increasingly widespread dual-clutch transmission design.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile-quarterly] The magazine started in Spring of 1962 with the subtitle "The Connoisseur's Magazine of Motoring Today, Yesterday, and Tomorrow" or in the words of the founder—"a cross between *The New Yorker* and *Encyclopædia Britannica* in the world of auto mania".
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile-quarterly] Scott Bailey (September 4, 1924 to June 26, 2012), working from offices in New York City.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile-quarterly] In 1963, an "office of publication" was opened in Kutztown, Pennsylvania, which operated first as Automobile Quarterly, Inc.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile-quarterly] Bailey retired to live in the English Cotswolds and CBS Magazines purchased *Automobile Quarterly* in 1986 and then sold the magazine to Kutztown Publishing in 1988.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile-quarterly] In October 2000, *Automobile Quarterly* was sold to a newly formed company, Automobile Heritage Publishing & Communications, LLC, and relocated to New Albany, Indiana.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile-quarterly] 52 (1) was the last issue published, in 2012.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile-quarterly] Kaye Bowles Durnell, the final editor, ceased publication in 2012 and stored the materials.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile-quarterly] In late 2018, she donated the Automobile Quarterly collection to America's Packard Museum in Dayton, Ohio.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile-quarterly] The Museum is digitizing samples from the collection and they are available on the Museum's Omeka site.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] A **car**, or an **automobile**, is a motor vehicle with wheels.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Most definitions of cars state that they run primarily on roads, seat 1-8 people, have four wheels, and mainly transport people rather than cargo.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] There are over 1.6 billion cars in use worldwide as of 2025.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] The French inventor Nicolas-Joseph Cugnot built the first steam-powered road vehicle in 1769, while the Swiss inventor François Isaac de Rivaz designed and constructed the first internal combustion-powered automobile in 1808.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] The modern car—a practical, marketable automobile for everyday use—was invented in 1886, when the German inventor Carl Benz patented his Benz Patent-Motorwagen.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Commercial cars became widely available during the 20th century.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] The 1901 Oldsmobile Curved Dash and the 1908 Ford Model T, both American cars, are widely considered the first mass-produced and mass-affordable cars, respectively.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Cars were rapidly adopted in the US, where they replaced horse-drawn carriages.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] In Europe and other parts of the world, demand for automobiles did not increase until after World War II.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] In the 21st century, car usage is still increasing rapidly, especially in China, India, and other newly industrialised countries.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Cars have controls for driving, parking, passenger comfort, and a variety of lamps.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Over the decades, additional features and controls have been added to vehicles, making them progressively more complex.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] These include rear-reversing cameras, air conditioning, navigation systems, and in-car entertainment.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Most cars in use in the early 2020s are propelled by an internal combustion engine, fueled by the combustion of fossil fuels.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Electric cars, which were invented early in the history of the car, became commercially available in the 2000s and widespread in the 2020s.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] The transition from fossil-fuel-powered cars to electric cars is a central feature of most climate change mitigation scenarios.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] There are costs and benefits to car use.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] The costs to the individual include acquiring the vehicle, interest payments (if the car is financed), repairs and maintenance, fuel, depreciation, driving time, parking fees, taxes, and insurance.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] The costs to society include resources used to produce cars and fuel, maintaining roads, land-use, road congestion, air pollution, noise pollution, public health, and disposing of the vehicle at the end of its life.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Traffic collisions are the largest cause of injury-related deaths worldwide.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Personal benefits include on-demand transportation, mobility, independence, and convenience.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Societal benefits include economic benefits, such as job and wealth creation from the automotive industry, transportation provision, and societal wellbeing from leisure and travel opportunities.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] People's ability to move flexibly from place to place has far-reaching implications for society.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] The English word *car* is believed to originate from Latin *carrus*/*carrum* "wheeled vehicle" or (via Old North French) Middle English **carre** "two-wheeled cart", both of which in turn derive from Gaulish **karros** "chariot".
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] It originally referred to any wheeled horse-drawn vehicle, such as a cart, carriage, or wagon.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] The word also occurs in other Celtic languages.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] "Motor car", attested from 1895, is the usual formal term in British English.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] "Autocar", a variant likewise attested from 1895 and literally meaning "self-propelled car", is now considered archaic.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] "Horseless carriage" is attested from 1895.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] "Automobile", a classical compound derived from Ancient Greek **autós** (αὐτός) "self" and Latin **mobilis** "movable", entered English from French and was first adopted by the Automobile Club of Great Britain in 1897.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] It fell out of favour in Britain and is now used chiefly in North America, where the abbreviated form "auto" commonly appears as an adjective in compound formations like "auto industry" and "auto mechanic".
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] In 1649, Hans Hautsch of Nuremberg built a clockwork-driven carriage.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] The first steam-powered vehicle was designed by Ferdinand Verbiest, a Flemish member of a Jesuit mission in China around 1672.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] It was a 65-centimetre-long (26 in) scale-model toy for the Kangxi Emperor that was unable to carry a driver or a passenger.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] It is not known with certainty if Verbiest's model was successfully built or run.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Nicolas-Joseph Cugnot is widely credited with building the first full-scale, self-propelled mechanical vehicle in about 1769; he created a steam-powered tricycle.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] He also constructed two steam tractors for the French Army, one of which is preserved in the French National Conservatory of Arts and Crafts.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] His inventions were limited by problems with water supply and maintaining steam pressure.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] In 1801, Richard Trevithick built and demonstrated his Puffing Devil road locomotive, believed by many to be the first demonstration of a steam-powered road vehicle.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] It was unable to maintain sufficient steam pressure for long periods and was of little practical use.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] The development of external combustion (also known as steam) engines is detailed in the history of the car.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Still, it is often treated separately from the development of cars in their modern understanding.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] A variety of steam-powered road vehicles were used during the first part of the 19th century, including steam cars, steam buses, phaetons, and steam rollers.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] In the United Kingdom, sentiment against them led to the Locomotive Acts of 1865.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] In 1807, Nicéphore Niépce and his brother Claude created what was probably the world's first internal combustion engine (which they called a Pyréolophore), but installed it in a boat on the river Saone in France.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Coincidentally, in 1807, the Swiss inventor François Isaac de Rivaz designed his own "de Rivaz internal combustion engine", and used it to develop the world's first vehicle to be powered by such an engine.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] The Niépces' Pyréolophore was fuelled by a mixture of Lycopodium powder (dried spores of the Lycopodium plant), finely crushed coal dust, and resin that were mixed with oil, whereas de Rivaz used a mixture of hydrogen and oxygen.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Neither design was successful, as was the case with others, such as Samuel Brown, Samuel Morey, and Etienne Lenoir, who each built vehicles (usually adapted carriages or carts) powered by internal combustion engines.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] In November 1881, French inventor Gustave Trouvé demonstrated a three-wheeled car powered by electricity at the International Exposition of Electricity.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Several other German engineers, including Gottlieb Daimler, Wilhelm Maybach, Siegfried Marcus, and Carl Benz were also working on cars and engines at about the same time.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] In 1879, Benz was granted a patent for a stationary engine.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] He had long dreamed of applying the internal combustion engine to produce a horseless carriage and began work on it in 1884.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] In 1885 he produced his first prototype car, the Benz Patent-Motorwagen Nr.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] On 29 January 1886 he applied for a patent for it, which was granted on 2 November of that year.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Benz further developed the Patent-Motorwagen, and had sufficient confidence in this to drive into Mannheim and have his vehicle written up in the *Neue Badische Landeszeitung* of 4 June 1886.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Benz' first production car, the Patent-Motorwagen Model 2, was produced in single-digit numbers in 1887–88.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Frenchman Émile Roger, already producing Benz engines under license, had added the Benz car to his product line in 1888.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Perhaps 60 of the Model 3 were produced between 1889 and 1893, the majority assembled in Paris from kits by Émile Roger.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Many historians consider Benz' advances so significant that they largely credit him as the inventor of the car and regard his 1886 patent as the birth of the modern car.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] In August 1888, Bertha Benz, the wife and business partner of Carl Benz, undertook the first road trip by an internal combustion engine car, to prove the road-worthiness of her husband's invention.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] In 1896, Carl Benz designed and patented the first internal-combustion flat engine, called *boxermotor*.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] During the last years of the 19th century, Benz was the largest car company in the world with 572 units produced in 1899 and, because of its size, Benz & Cie. became a joint-stock company.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] The first motor car in central Europe and one of the first factory-made cars in the world was produced by the Czech company Nesselsdorfer Wagenbau (later renamed to Tatra) in 1897, the Präsident automobil.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Daimler and Maybach founded Daimler Motoren Gesellschaft (DMG) in Cannstatt in 1890, and sold their first car in 1892 under the brand name *Daimler*.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] It was a horse-drawn stagecoach built by another manufacturer, which they retrofitted with an engine of their design.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] By 1895, about 30 vehicles had been built by Daimler and Maybach, either at the Daimler works or at the Hotel Hermann, where they set up shop after disputes with their backers.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Benz, Maybach, and the Daimler team seem to have been unaware of each other's early work.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] They never worked together; by the time of the merger of the two companies, Daimler and Maybach were no longer part of DMG.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Daimler died in 1900, and later that year, Maybach designed an engine named *Daimler-Mercedes* that was installed in a specially ordered model built to specifications set by Emil Jellinek.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] This was a limited production run of vehicles for Jellinek to race and market in his country.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Two years later, in 1902, a new model of the DMG car was produced and named Mercedes after the Maybach engine, which generated 35 hp.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Maybach left DMG shortly thereafter and opened his own business.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Rights to the *Daimler* brand name were sold to other manufacturers.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] In 1890, Émile Levassor (who had bought a Benz Patent-Motorwagen Model 2 in 1888) and Armand Peugeot of France began producing vehicles with Daimler engines, and so laid the foundation of the automotive industry in France.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] In 1891, Auguste Doriot and his Peugeot colleague Louis Rigoulot completed the longest trip by a petrol-driven vehicle when their self-designed and built Daimler-powered Peugeot Type 3 completed 2,100 kilometres (1,300 mi) from Valentigney to Paris and Brest and back again.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] They were attached to the first Paris–Brest–Paris bicycle race, but finished six days after the winning cyclist, Charles Terront.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] The first design for an American car with a petrol internal combustion engine was made in 1877 by George Selden of Rochester, New York.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Selden applied for a patent for a car in 1879, but the patent application expired because the vehicle was never built.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] After a delay of 16 years and a series of attachments to his application, on 5 November 1895, Selden was granted a US patent (U.S. patent 549,160) for a two-stroke car engine, which hindered, more than encouraged, development of cars in the United States.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] His patent was challenged by Henry Ford and others, and overturned in 1911.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] In 1893, the first running, petrol-driven American car was built and road-tested by the Duryea brothers of Springfield, Massachusetts.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] The first public run of the Duryea Motor Wagon took place on 21 September 1893, on Taylor Street in Metro Center Springfield.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Studebaker, subsidiary of a long-established wagon and coach manufacturer, started to build cars in 1897 and commenced sales of electric vehicles in 1902 and petrol vehicles in 1904.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] In Britain, there had been several attempts to build steam cars with varying degrees of success, with Thomas Rickett even attempting a production run in 1860.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Santler from Malvern is recognised by the Veteran Car Club of Great Britain as having made the first petrol-driven car in the country in 1894, followed by Frederick William Lanchester in 1895, but these were both one-offs.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] The first production vehicles in Great Britain came from the Daimler Company, a company founded by Harry J.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Lawson in 1896, after purchasing the right to use the name of the engines.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Lawson's company made its first car in 1897, and they bore the name Daimler.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] In 1892, German engineer Rudolf Diesel was granted a patent for a "New Rational Combustion Engine".
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] In 1897, he built the first diesel engine.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Steam-, electric-, and petrol-driven vehicles competed for a few decades, with petrol internal combustion engines achieving dominance in the 1910s.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Although various pistonless rotary engine designs have attempted to compete with the conventional piston and crankshaft design, only Mazda's version of the Wankel engine has had more than very limited success.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] All in all, it is estimated that over 100,000 patents have contributed to the modern automobile and motorcycle.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Large-scale, production-line manufacturing of affordable cars was started by Ransom Olds in 1901 at his Oldsmobile factory in Lansing, Michigan, and based upon stationary assembly line techniques pioneered by Marc Isambard Brunel at the Portsmouth Block Mills, England, in 1802.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] The assembly line style of mass production and interchangeable parts had been pioneered in the US by Thomas Blanchard in 1821, at the Springfield Armory in Springfield, Massachusetts.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] This concept was greatly expanded by Henry Ford, beginning in 1913 with the world's first *moving* assembly line for cars at the Highland Park Ford Plant.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] As a result, Ford's cars came off the line in 15-minute intervals, much faster than previous methods, increasing productivity eightfold while using less labour (from 12.5 manhours to 1 hour 33 minutes).
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] It was so successful, paint became a bottleneck.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Only Japan black would dry fast enough, forcing the company to drop the variety of colours available before 1913, until fast-drying Duco lacquer was developed in 1926.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] This is the source of Ford's apocryphal remark, "any color as long as it's black".
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] In 1914, an assembly line worker could buy a Model T with four months' pay.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Ford's complex safety procedures—especially assigning each worker to a specific location rather than allowing them to roam—dramatically reduced injury rates.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] The combination of high wages and high efficiency is called "Fordism" and was copied by most major industries.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] The efficiency gains from the assembly line also coincided with the US's economic rise.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] The assembly line forced workers to move at a certain pace with very repetitive motions, which led to more output per worker, while other countries used less productive methods.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] In the automotive industry, its success was dominant and quickly spread worldwide, with the founding of Ford France and Ford Britain in 1911, Ford Denmark in 1923, and Ford Germany in 1925; in 1921, Citroën was the first native European manufacturer to adopt the production method.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Soon, companies had to have assembly lines or risk going bankrupt; by 1930, 250 companies that did not have assembly lines disappeared.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] The development of automotive technology was rapid, due in part to the hundreds of small manufacturers competing to gain the world's attention.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Key developments included electric ignition and the electric self-starter (both by Charles Kettering, for the Cadillac Motor Company in 1910–1911), independent suspension, and four-wheel brakes.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Since the 1920s, nearly all cars have been mass-produced to meet market needs, so marketing plans have often heavily influenced car design.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Sloan who established the idea of different makes of cars produced by one company, called the General Motors Companion Make Program, so that buyers could "move up" as their fortunes improved.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Reflecting the rapid pace of change, makers shared parts with one another, resulting in lower costs across all price ranges.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Most British small-car assemblers, from Abbey to Xtra, had gone under.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Citroën did the same in France, coming to cars in 1919; between them and other cheap cars in reply such as Renault's 10CV and Peugeot's 5CV, they produced 550,000 cars in 1925, and Mors, Hurtu, and others could not compete.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Germany's first mass-manufactured car, the Opel 4PS *Laubfrosch* (Tree Frog), came off the line at Rüsselsheim in 1924, soon making Opel the top car builder in Germany, with 37.5 per cent of the market.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] In Japan, car production was very limited before World War II.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Only a handful of companies produced vehicles in limited numbers, and these were small, three-wheeled for commercial use, like Daihatsu, or the result of partnerships with European companies, like Isuzu building the Wolseley A-9 in 1922.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Mitsubishi was also partnered with Fiat and built the Mitsubishi Model A based on a Fiat vehicle.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Toyota, Nissan, Suzuki, Mazda, and Honda began as companies producing non-automotive products before the war, then switched to car production in the 1950s.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Kiichiro Toyoda's decision to take Toyoda Loom Works into automobile manufacturing would eventually lead to the formation of Toyota Motor Corporation, the world's largest automobile manufacturer.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Subaru, meanwhile, was formed from a conglomerate of six companies that banded together as Fuji Heavy Industries, as a result of having been broken up under *keiretsu* legislation.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Most cars in use in the mid 2020s run on petrol burnt in an internal combustion engine (ICE).
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Some cities ban older, more polluting petrol-driven cars, and some countries plan to ban sales in the future.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] However, some environmental groups say this phase-out of fossil fuel vehicles must be brought forward to limit climate change.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Production of petrol-fuelled cars peaked in 2017.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Other hydrocarbon fossil fuels also burnt by deflagration (rather than detonation) in ICE cars include diesel, autogas, and CNG.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Removal of fossil fuel subsidies, concerns about oil dependence, tightening environmental laws and restrictions on greenhouse gas emissions are propelling work on alternative power systems for cars.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] This includes hybrid vehicles, plug-in electric vehicles, and hydrogen vehicles.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] As of 2025 one in four cars sold is electric but, despite rapid growth, less than one in twenty cars on the world's roads were fully electric and plug-in hybrid cars by the end of 2024.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Cars for racing or speed records have sometimes employed jet or rocket engines, but these are impractical for common use.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Oil consumption has increased rapidly in the 20th and 21st centuries because there are more cars; the 1980s oil glut even fuelled the sales of low-economy vehicles in OECD countries.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] In almost all hybrid (even mild hybrid) and pure electric cars, regenerative braking recovers and returns to a battery some energy which would otherwise be wasted by friction brakes getting hot.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Although all cars must have friction brakes (front disc brakes and either disc or drum rear brakes) for emergency stops, regenerative braking improves efficiency, particularly in city driving.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Cars are equipped with controls for driving, passenger comfort, and safety, normally operated by a combination of feet and hands, and occasionally by voice in 21st-century cars.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] These controls include a steering wheel, pedals for operating the brakes and controlling the car's speed (and, in a manual transmission car, a clutch pedal), a shift lever or stick for changing gears, and several buttons and dials for turning on lights, ventilation, and other functions.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Modern cars' controls are now standardised, such as the location of the accelerator and brake, but this was not always the case.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Controls are evolving in response to new technologies, for example, the electric car and the integration of mobile communications.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Some of the original controls are no longer required.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] For example, all cars once had controls for the choke valve, clutch, ignition timing, and a crank instead of an electric starter.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] However, new controls have also been added to vehicles, making them more complex.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] These include air conditioning, navigation systems, and in-car entertainment.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Another trend is the replacement of physical knobs and switches with secondary controls, such as touchscreen controls, such as BMW's *iDrive* and Ford's *MyFord Touch*.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Another change is that while early cars' pedals were physically linked to the brake mechanism and throttle, in the early 2020s, cars have increasingly replaced these physical linkages with electronic controls.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] More costly upper-class and luxury cars are equipped with features earlier such as massage seats and collision avoidance systems.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Dedicated automotive fuses and circuit breakers prevent damage from electrical overload.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Cars are typically fitted with multiple types of lights.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Interior ceiling lights in the car are usually fitted for the driver and passengers.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Some vehicles also have a boot light and, more rarely, an engine compartment light.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] During the late 20th and early 21st century, cars increased in weight due to batteries, modern steel safety cages, anti-lock brakes, airbags, and "more-powerful—if more efficient—engines" and, as of 2019, typically weigh between 1 and 3 tonnes (1.1 and 3.3 short tons; 0.98 and 2.95 long tons).
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Heavier cars are safer for the driver from a crash perspective, but more dangerous for other vehicles and road users.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] The weight of a car influences fuel consumption and performance, with more weight resulting in increased fuel consumption and decreased performance.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] The Wuling Hongguang Mini EV, a typical city car, weighs about 700 kilograms (1,500 lb).
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Heavier cars include SUVs and extended-length SUVs like the Suburban.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Some places tax heavier cars more: as well as improving pedestrian safety, this can encourage manufacturers to use materials such as recycled aluminium instead of steel.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] It has been suggested that one benefit of subsidising charging infrastructure is that cars can use lighter batteries.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Most cars are designed to carry multiple occupants, often with four or five seats.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Cars with five seats typically seat two passengers in the front and three in the rear.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Full-size cars and large sport utility vehicles can often carry six, seven, or more occupants, depending on seat arrangement.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] On the other hand, sports cars are most often designed with only two seats.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Utility vehicles like pickup trucks combine seating with extra cargo or utility functionality.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] The differing needs for passenger capacity and their luggage or cargo space has resulted in the availability of a large variety of body styles to meet individual consumer requirements that include, among others, the sedan/saloon, hatchback, station wagon/estate, coupe, and minivan.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Mary Ward became one of the first documented car fatalities in 1869 in Parsonstown, Ireland, and Henry Bliss one of the US's first pedestrian car casualties in 1899 in New York City.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] There are now standard tests for safety in new cars, such as the Euro and US NCAP tests, and insurance-industry-backed tests by the Insurance Institute for Highway Safety (IIHS).
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] However, not all such tests consider the safety of people outside the car, such as drivers of other cars, pedestrians and cyclists.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Some countries are tightening safety regulations for new cars, for example to mandate data recorders and automated braking.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] The costs of car usage, which may include the cost of: acquiring the vehicle, repairs and auto maintenance, fuel, depreciation, driving time, parking fees, taxes, and insurance, are weighed against the cost of the alternatives, and the value of the benefits—perceived and real—of vehicle usage.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] The benefits may include on-demand transportation, mobility, independence, and convenience, and emergency power.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Societal benefits may include economic benefits, such as job and wealth creation, from car production and maintenance, transportation provision, societal wellbeing derived from leisure and travel opportunities, and revenue generation from the tax opportunities.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] The ability of humans to move flexibly from place to place has far-reaching implications for the nature of societies.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Trucks' share of US vehicles produced has tripled since 1975.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Though vehicle fuel efficiency has increased within each category, the overall trend toward less efficient types of vehicles has offset some of the benefits of greater fuel economy and reductions in pollution and carbon dioxide emissions.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Without the shift towards SUVs, energy use per unit distance could have fallen 30% more than it did from 2010 to 2022.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Car production and use have a large number of environmental impacts: it causes local air pollution plastic pollution and contributes to greenhouse gas emissions and climate change.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Cars and vans caused 10% of energy-related carbon dioxide emissions in 2022.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] As of 2023, electric cars produce about half the emissions over their lifetime as diesel and petrol cars.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] This is set to improve as countries produce more of their electricity from low-carbon sources.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Cars consume almost a quarter of world oil production as of 2019.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Cities planned around cars are often less dense, which leads to further emissions, as they are less walkable, for instance.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] A growing demand for large SUVs is driving up emissions from cars.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Cars are a major cause of air pollution, which stems from exhaust gas in diesel and petrol cars and from dust from brakes, tyres, and road wear.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Heavy metals and microplastics (from tyres) are also released into the environment, during production, use, and at the end of life.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Mining related to car manufacturing and oil spills both cause water pollution.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Animals and plants are often negatively affected by cars through habitat destruction and fragmentation caused by the road network, as well as pollution.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Animals are also killed every year on roads by cars, referred to as roadkill.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] More recent road developments are including significant environmental mitigation in their designs, such as green bridges (designed to allow wildlife crossings) and creating wildlife corridors.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Governments use fiscal policies, such as road tax, to discourage the purchase and use of more polluting cars; Vehicle emission standards ban the sale of new highly pollution cars.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Many countries plan to stop selling fossil cars altogether between 2025 and 2050.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Various cities have implemented low-emission zones, banning old fossil fuel and Amsterdam is planning to ban fossil fuel cars completely.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Some cities make it easier for people to choose other forms of transport, such as cycling.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Many Chinese cities limit licensing of fossil fuel cars.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Mass production of personal motor vehicles in the United States and other developed countries with extensive territories, such as Australia, Argentina, and France, vastly increased individual and group mobility and greatly expanded economic development in urban, suburban, exurban, and rural areas.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Growth in the popularity of cars and commuting has led to traffic congestion.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Moscow, Istanbul, Bogotá, Mexico City and São Paulo were the world's most congested cities in 2018 according to INRIX, a data analytics company.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] In the United States, the transport divide and car dependency resulting from domination of car-based transport systems presents barriers to employment in low-income neighbourhoods, with many low-income individuals and families forced to run cars they cannot afford in order to maintain their income.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Dependency on automobiles by African Americans may result in exposure to the hazards of driving while black and other types of racial discrimination related to buying, financing and insuring them.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Air pollution from cars increases the risk of a number of diseases, including stroke, heart disease, chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD), lung cancer, respiratory infections and aggravated asthma.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Air pollution is also linked to global impacts on all aspects of sexual reproduction from male and female fertility to fetal development, birth outcomes, and long-term health of offspring.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Children are extra vulnerable to air pollution, as their bodies are still developing and air pollution in children is linked to the development of asthma, childhood cancer, and neurocognitive issues such as autism.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] The growth in popularity of the car allowed cities to sprawl, therefore encouraging more travel by car, resulting in inactivity and obesity, which in turn can lead to increased risk of a variety of diseases.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] When places are designed around cars, children have fewer opportunities to go places by themselves and lose opportunities to become more independent.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Intensive development of conventional battery electric vehicles is continuing into the 2020s, for example lithium iron phosphate batteries are safer and cheaper.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Other car technologies that are under development include wireless charging.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Software is increasing and may have many new uses, for example automatically not hitting pedestrians.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] New materials which may replace steel car bodies include aluminium, fibreglass, carbon fibre, biocomposites, and carbon nanotubes.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Telematics technology is allowing more and more people to share cars, on a pay-as-you-go basis, through car share and carpool schemes.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Communication is also evolving due to connected car systems.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Microwave weapons which can disable cars are being tested.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Fully self-driving vehicles, also known as autonomous cars, already exist as robotaxis in some locations.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Laws for the regulation of self-driving cars will need updating before widespread deployment can happen.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Car-share arrangements and carpooling are also increasingly popular, in the US and Europe.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Services like car sharing offer residents to "share" a vehicle rather than own a car in already congested neighbourhoods.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] The automotive industry designs, develops, manufactures, markets, and sells the world's motor vehicles, more than three-quarters of which are cars.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] In 2020, there were 56 million cars manufactured worldwide, down from 67 million the previous year.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] The automotive industry in China produces by far the most (20 million in 2020), followed by Japan (seven million), then Germany, South Korea, and India.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] The largest market is China, followed by the US.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] There are around 1.644 billion cars in use worldwide as of January 2025; they burn over a trillion litres (0.26×10^12 US gal; 0.22×10^12 imp gal) of petrol and diesel fuel yearly, consuming about 50 exajoules (14,000 TWh) of energy.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] The number of cars is increasing rapidly in China and India.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] In the opinion of some, urban transport systems based around the car have proved unsustainable, consuming excessive energy, affecting the health of populations, and delivering a declining level of service despite increasing investment.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Many of these negative effects fall disproportionately on those social groups who are also least likely to own and drive cars.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] The sustainable transport movement focuses on solutions to these problems.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] The car industry is also facing increasing competition from the public transport sector, as some people re-evaluate their use of private vehicles.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] In July 2021, the European Commission introduced the "Fit for 55" legislation package, outlining crucial directives for the automotive sector's future.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] According to this package, by 2035, all newly sold cars in the European market must be Zero-emissions vehicles.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Established alternatives for some aspects of car use include public transport such as busses, trolleybusses, trains, subways, tramways, light rail, cycling, and walking.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Bicycle sharing systems have been established in China and many European cities, including Copenhagen and Amsterdam.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Similar programmes have been developed in large US cities.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Additional individual modes of transport, such as personal rapid transit could serve as an alternative to cars if they prove to be socially accepted.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] A study which checked the costs and the benefits of introducing Low Traffic Neighbourhood in London found the benefits overpass the costs approximately by 100 times in the first 20 years and the difference is growing over time.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] Motorsport is a sport involving high speed racing and drifting.
[src:dodge-coronet/automobile] It includes various racing series such as Formula One, IndyCar Series, NASCAR, World Rally Championship and MotoGP.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] The functional design and development of a modern motor vehicle is typically done by a large team from many different disciplines also included within automotive engineering, however, design roles are not associated with requirements for professional- or chartered-engineer qualifications.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] Automotive design in this context focuses primarily on developing the visual appearance or aesthetics of vehicles, while also becoming involved in the creation of product concepts.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] Automotive design as a professional vocation is practiced by designers who may have an art background and a degree in industrial design or in transportation design.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] For the terminology used in the field, see the glossary of automotive design.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] The task of the design team is usually split into three main aspects: exterior design, interior design, and color and trim design.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] Graphic design is also an aspect of automotive design; this is generally shared amongst the design team as the lead designer sees fit.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] The design focuses not only on the isolated outer shape of automobile parts, but concentrates on the combination of form and function, starting from the vehicle package.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] The aesthetic value will need to correspond to ergonomic functionality and utility features as well.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] Though not all the new vehicular gadgets are to be designated as factory standard items, some of them may be integral to determining the future course of any specific vehicular models.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] The design team(s) responsible for the exterior of the vehicle develops the proportions, shape, and surface details of the vehicle.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] Exterior design is first done by a series of manual sketches and digital drawings.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] Progressively, more detailed drawings are executed and approved by appropriate layers of management, followed by digital rendering to images.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] Consumer feedback is generally sought at this point to help iteratively refine vehicle concepts according to the targeted market and will continue throughout the rest of the design refinement process.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] After more progressive refinement, industrial plasticine and or digital models are developed from and along with the drawings and images.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] The data from these models are then used to create quarter-scale and finally full-sized mock-ups of the final design.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] With three- and five-axis CNC milling machines, the clay model is first designed in a computer program and then "carved" using the machine and large amounts of clay.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] Even in times of photorealistic (three-dimensional) software and virtual models on power walls, the clay model is still the most important tool for a final evaluation of the exterior design of a vehicle and, therefore, is used throughout the industry.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] The designer responsible for the vehicles' interior develops the proportions, shape, placement, and surfaces for the instrument panel, seats, door trim panels, headliner, pillar trims, etc.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] Here the emphasis is on ergonomics and the comfort of the passengers.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] The procedure here is the same as with exterior design (sketch, digital model, and clay model).
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] The color and trim (or color and materials) designer is responsible for the research, design, and development of all interior and exterior colors and materials used on a vehicle.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] These include paints, plastics, fabric designs, leather, grains, carpet, headliner, wood trim, and so on.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] Color, contrast, texture, and pattern must be carefully combined to give the vehicle a unique interior environment experience.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] Designers work closely with exterior and interior designers.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] Designers draw inspiration from other design disciplines such as industrial design, fashion, home furnishing, architecture, and sometimes product design.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] Specific research is done into global trends to design for projects two to three model years in the future.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] Trend boards are created from this research to keep track of design influences as they relate to the automotive industry.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] The designer then uses this information to develop themes and concepts that are then further refined and tested on the vehicle models.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] The design team also develops graphics for items, such as badges, decals, dials, switches, kick or tread strips, or liveries.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] The sketches and rendering are transformed into 3D digital surface modeling and rendering for real-time evaluation with Math data in the initial stages.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] During the development process succeeding phases will require the 3D model fully developed to meet the aesthetic requirements of a designer as well as all engineering and manufacturing requirements.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] The fully developed CAS digital model will be re-developed for manufacturing meeting the Class-A surface standards that involve both technical as well as aesthetics.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] A Product Engineering team will further develop this data.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] These modelers usually have a background in industrial design or sometimes tooling engineering in the case of some Class-A modelers.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] Autodesk Alias and ICEM Surf are the two most widely used software tools for Class-A development.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] Uniform surface continuity is critical to ensure Class-A surface standards.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] The continuity of the areas is between the quality grades G0 through G3, with G3 guaranteeing the cleanest patch-to-patch transitions.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] The design process occurs concurrently with other product engineers who will be engineering the styling data for meeting performance, manufacturing, and safety regulations.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] From mid-phase, back-and-forth interactions between the designers and product engineers culminate into a finished product being manufacturing-ready.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] Apart from this the engineering team parallelly works in the following areas.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] Product Engineering (Body In White Sheetmetal Design and Plastic engineering), NVH Development team, Prototype development, Powertrain engineering, Physical Vehicle validation, Tool and Die development, and Manufacturing process design.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] The design team for a specific model consists of a chief designer and an exterior as well as an interior designer.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] In some cases, all three roles are done by one designer.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] Several junior designers are involved in the development process as well and make specific contributions all overseen by the chief designer.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] Apart from this, the color and trim designer works closely with other designers.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] The clay model team and digital model team work closely with the styling team all located within the studio.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] Apart from this, there would be studio heads, studio managers, and prototype engineers who would work across all teams in the studio.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] The total team size for developing a full car usually ranges from 25 to 40 members and the development time lasts for more than 24 months until signed-off for tooling and production.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] After that, a smaller team would be working until the vehicle launch.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] In the early days of the automobile, manufacturers prioritized function over form, focusing on building simple, reliable, and affordable vehicles.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] Some automakers began incorporating artists to combine styling with engineering.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] Visual appeal remained secondary to technical and safety advancements until the 1930s, an era that, despite its financial challenges, became a high point of creative coachbuilding.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] World War II halted the momentum, but it evolved when the industry restarted in the late 1940s, heavily influenced by the Jet Age.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] However, the artwork and models created by designers are routinely destroyed so as not to be seen by competing automakers.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] Great car designers are visionary artists who can translate their ideas from sketches and models into tangible vehicles.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] Their work is a blend of artistry and engineering, shaped by collaborations with engineers who help bring their creative concepts to life.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] Some automobile forms have served to influence the success and careers of successive designers.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] In the United States, automotive design reached a turning point in the 1920s when the American national automobile market began reaching saturation.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] To maintain unit sales, General Motors head Alfred P.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] Sloan Jr. suggested annual model-year design changes to convince car owners that they needed to buy a new replacement each year, an idea borrowed from the bicycle industry (though Sloan usually gets the credit or blame).
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] Critics called his strategy planned obsolescence.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] Sloan preferred the term "dynamic obsolescence".
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] This strategy had far-reaching effects on the auto business, the field of product design, and eventually the American economy.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] The smaller automakers could not maintain the pace and expense of yearly re-styling.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] Henry Ford did not like the model-year change because he clung to an engineer's notions of simplicity, the economics of scale, and design integrity.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] GM surpassed Ford's sales in 1931 and became the dominant company in the industry thereafter.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] The frequent design changes also made it necessary to use a body-on-frame rather than the lighter but less adaptable monocoque design used by most European automakers.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] In the 1930s, Chrysler's innovations with aerodynamics helped launch the Chrysler Airflow in 1934, which was revolutionary and radical compared to contemporary vehicles.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] However, inadequate consumer acceptance of the advanced appearance of the cars forced a re-design of succeeding models of the Airflow.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] This marketing experience made the entire industry take note of the high risks involved in incorporating major design advancements into their production cars.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] A major influence on American auto styling and marketing was Harley Earl, who is credited with inventing the idea of a concept car, and who brought the tailfin and other aeronautical design references to auto design starting with the rear fenders of the 1948 Cadillac.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] Another notable designer was Chrysler group's designer Virgil Exner, who developed the Forward look design in the mid-1950s.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] Exner is also credited with using wind tunnel testing to justify incorporating tailfins, thus moving the company away from boxy-looking cars into more aerodynamic and futuristic designs that were influenced by rockets after WWII.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] Other influential automotive designers include Raymond Loewy, who was responsible for a number of Studebaker vehicles such as the Avanti, and Gordon Buehrig, who was responsible for the Auburn 851, as well as the Cord 810 and 812.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] Starting in the 1960s, Dick Teague, who spent most of his career with American Motors Corporation (AMC), originated the concept of using interchangeable body panels so as to create a wide array of different vehicles using the same stampings, starting with the AMC Cavalier.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] Teague was responsible for automotive designs such as the two-seat AMC AMX muscle car, the subcompact Gremlin, the Pacer, and Matador coupe, as well as the original and market segment-creating, Jeep Cherokee.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] Additionally during the 1960s, Ford's first-generation Ford Mustang and Thunderbird marked another era leading into new market segments from Detroit.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] The Ford Mustang achieved record sales in its first year of production and established the pony car segment.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] Personal injury litigation has affected the design and appearance of the car in the 20th century.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] Until World War I, most automakers were concerned with mechanical reliability rather than the external appearance of their cars.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] Later, luxury and aesthetics became a demand, and also an effective marketing tool.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] Designs from each nation with their own strong cultural identity are reflected in their exterior and interior designs.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] World War II slowed the progress, but after the early 1950s, Italian designers set the trend and remained the driving force until the early part of the 1980s.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] In France notable designs came from Bugatti and Avions Voisin.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] Of the mass-selling cars, Citroën launched their vehicles with innovative designs and engineering, aided by the styling of Flaminio Bertoni as evident from the Citroën DS.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] After World War II, with the decline of the coachbuilding industry, French automakers (except Citroën) followed British and other popular trends until they gained financial stability.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] During the 1980s, manufacturers like Renault cultivated their own strong design identities with designers like Patrick Le Quément.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] Peugeot, which was dependent on Pininfarina since the early post-war period, later established its own brand identity from the 1980s onwards.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] Its other company, Citroën, still retains its distinctive French innovations for its designs.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] Great Britain was Europe's leading manufacturer of automobiles until the late-1960s.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] During that era, there were more British-based automakers than in the rest of Europe combined.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] The British automobile industry catered to all segments ranging from compact, budget, sports, utility, and luxury-type cars.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] Car design in Britain was markedly different from other European designs largely because British designers were not influenced by other European art or design movements, as well as the British clay modelers, used a different sweep set.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] British cars until World War II were sold in most of the British colonies.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] Innovations in vehicle packaging and chassis engineering combined with global familiarity with British designs meant vehicles were acceptable to public tastes at that time.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] British skilled resources such as panel beaters, die machinists, and clay modelers were also available partly due to their involvement with the motorsport industry.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] Still, during the 1960s, British manufacturers sought professional help from Italian designers and studios such as Giovanni Michelotti, Ercole Spada, and Pininfarina.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] Notable British contributions to automobile designs were the Morris Mini by Alec Issigonis, several Jaguar Cars by Sir William Lyons and Malcolm Sayer, Aston Martin DB Series, and several cars from Triumph and MG.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] Ford Europe, based in Great Britain, is notable for the Ford Sierra line, a work of Uwe Bahnsen, Robert Lutz, and Patrick le Quément.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] Other notable British designers include William Towns for Aston Martin, and David Bache for Land Rover and Range Rover, and Ian Callum for Jaguar.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] During the complex changes in the British car industry in the 1990s and beyond, a mix of designers worked on all of the remaining mainstream brands under one design director and in one studio.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] The director most involved was Geoff Upex, with his team of Richard Woolley, Dave Saddington, George Thomson, Alan Mobberley, and Martin Peach (colour and trim).
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] Germany is often considered the birthplace of industrial design with the Bauhaus School of Design, before it was closed down by the Nazi regime.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] Ferdinand Porsche and his family played a significant role in German design.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] Mercedes-Benz passenger cars were also in the luxury segment and played an important role in German car design.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] After the 1980s, German design evolved into a distinctive Teutonic style often to complement their highly engineered cars suited to Autobahns.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] The early German design clues of the present-day owe some part to Italian designers like Giovanni Michelotti, Ercole Spada, Bruno Sacco, and Giorgetto Giugiaro.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] During the mid- and late-20th century one of the most influential coach builders/designers in Germany was Karmann.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] German designs started gaining popularity after the 1980s, notable after the formation of Audi.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] Volkswagen, which was dependent on Marcello Gandini, Giorgetto Giugiaro, and Karmann, later formed the contemporary design language along with Audi.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] BMW entered the automobile design with sporty-looking everyday sedans using Giovanni Michelotti.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] These models were later enhanced by Ercole Spada into the 1980s, and Klaus Luthe until the mid-1990s.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] The American-born designer Chris Bangle was hired by BMW in the late-1990s to redefine the brand.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] Bangle incorporated new single-press technology for compound curves to add controversial styling elements to his designs.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] The Porsche family contribution was instrumental in the evolution of Porsche cars, while the Italian designer Bruno Sacco helped create various Mercedes Models from the 1960s to the 1990s.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] In Italy, Fiat and Alfa Romeo played a major role in car design.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] Many coachbuilders were dependent on these two major manufacturers.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] Italian manufacturers had a large presence in motorsports leading to several sport car manufacturers like Ferrari, Lancia, Lamborghini, Maserati, etc.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] During the late-1950s, Italian automobile designs gained global popularity coinciding with the modern fashion and architecture at that time around the world.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] Various design and technical schools in Turin turned out designers on a large scale.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] By the late-1960s, almost all Italian coachbuilders transformed into design studios catering to automakers around the world.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] The trend continued in the 1990s when the Japanese and Korean manufacturers sourced designs from these styling studios.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] Some Italian designers whose design services were sought globally include Aldo Brovarone, Giovanni Michelotti, Ercole Spada, Bruno Sacco, Marcello Gandini, Giorgetto Giugiaro, and Walter de Silva.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] Sweden had Volvo and Saab as domestic automakers, and the nation's northern location required that cars needed to withstand Nordic climate conditions.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] The Scandinavian design elements are known for their minimalism and simplicity.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] One of the early original Scandinavian designs was the Saab 92001 by Sixten Sason and Gunnar Ljungström.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] Koenigsegg, founded in the 1990s, became Sweden's first domestic producer of high end sports cars, with many of their models featuring in house designs by Swedish designers.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] Before World War II and until the early-1990s, Czechoslovakia had a strong presence in the automotive industry with manufacturers like Škoda, Jawa, Tatra, CZ, Praga, and Zetor.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] Czech automobiles were generally known for their originality in mechanical simplicity and designs were remarkably Bohemian as evident from Tatra cars and Jawa motorcycles.
[src:dodge-coronet/automotive-design] During the Communist regime, the design started falling back and ultimately the domestic automakers ended up as subsidiaries of EU-based companies.
[src:dodge-coronet/bonneville-salt-flats] The **Bonneville Salt Flats** are a densely packed salt pan in Tooele County in northwestern Utah, United States.
[src:dodge-coronet/bonneville-salt-flats] A remnant of the Pleistocene Lake Bonneville, it is the largest of many salt flats west of the Great Salt Lake.
[src:dodge-coronet/bonneville-salt-flats] It is public land managed by the Bureau of Land Management and is known for land speed records at the Bonneville Speedway.
[src:dodge-coronet/bonneville-salt-flats] The Flats are about 12 miles (19 km) long and 5 miles (8 km) wide, with a crust almost 5 ft (1.5m) thick at the center and less than one inch (2.5 cm) towards the edges.
[src:dodge-coronet/bonneville-salt-flats] It is estimated to hold 147 million tons of salt, about 90% of which is common table salt.
[src:dodge-coronet/bonneville-salt-flats] Geologist Grove Karl Gilbert named the area after Benjamin Bonneville, a U.S.
[src:dodge-coronet/bonneville-salt-flats] Army officer who explored the Intermountain West in the 1830s.
[src:dodge-coronet/bonneville-salt-flats] In 1907, Bill Rishel and two local businessmen tested the suitability of the salt for driving by taking a Pierce-Arrow onto its surface.
[src:dodge-coronet/bonneville-salt-flats] A railway line across the Flats was completed in 1910, marking the first permanent crossing.
[src:dodge-coronet/bonneville-salt-flats] The first land speed record was set there in 1914 by Teddy Tetzlaff.
[src:dodge-coronet/bonneville-salt-flats] The Pontiac Bonneville (former flagship sedan of the Pontiac motor division), the Triumph Bonneville motorcycle, and the Bonneville International media company are all named for the Flats.
[src:dodge-coronet/bonneville-salt-flats] The Bonneville Salt Flats hosts the annual US Flight Archery Championships.
[src:dodge-coronet/bonneville-salt-flats] The goal of flight archery is to shoot arrows from bows at the greatest distance possible.
[src:dodge-coronet/bonneville-salt-flats] The 1977 (archer Don Brown) and 1982 (archer Alan Webster) world records were set there.
[src:dodge-coronet/bonneville-salt-flats] The thickness of salt crust is a critical factor in racing use of the salt flats.
[src:dodge-coronet/bonneville-salt-flats] The Bureau of Land Management (BLM) has undertaken multiple studies on the topic; while a 2007 study determined that there was little change in the crust's thickness from 1988 to 2003, more recent studies have shown a reduction in thickness, especially in the northwest area where racing occurs.
[src:dodge-coronet/bonneville-salt-flats] The flats' overall area has contracted over the past several decades.
[src:dodge-coronet/bonneville-salt-flats] Many believe nearby evaporative potash mining is the primary factor.
[src:dodge-coronet/bonneville-salt-flats] Collaboration between racing organizations, the potash mine, and the BLM led to a pilot program begun in 1998 to release excess brine onto the salt flats during winter.
[src:dodge-coronet/bonneville-salt-flats] Plans to increase the volume of brine returned to the salt flats are hoped to halt loss of crust thickness, or possibly restore it where it has become too thin to sustain human use.
[src:dodge-coronet/bonneville-salt-flats] Land speed records and Land speed racing records have been set many times on the Bonneville Salt Flats.
[src:dodge-coronet/bonneville-salt-flats] The record for wheel-driven vehicles (449 MPH) was set there in 2018, and for rocket or jet propelled vehicles (630 MPH; since superseded) in 1970.
[src:dodge-coronet/bonneville-salt-flats] Motorcar racing has taken place at the salt flats since 1914.
[src:dodge-coronet/bonneville-salt-flats] Racing takes place at part of the Bonneville Salt Flats known as the Bonneville Speedway.
[src:dodge-coronet/bonneville-salt-flats] There are five major land speed events that take place at the Bonneville Salt Flats.
[src:dodge-coronet/bonneville-salt-flats] Bonneville "Speed Week" takes place mid-August followed by "World of Speed" in September and the "World Finals" take place early October.
[src:dodge-coronet/bonneville-salt-flats] These three events welcome cars, trucks, and motorcycles.
[src:dodge-coronet/bonneville-salt-flats] The "Bub Motorcycle Speed Trials" are for motorcycles only.
[src:dodge-coronet/bonneville-salt-flats] World records are contested at the Mike Cook ShootOut in September.
[src:dodge-coronet/bonneville-salt-flats] The Southern California Timing Association and the Utah Salt Flats Racing Association organizes and plans the multi-vehicle events, but all event promoters contribute to prepping and maintaining the salt.
[src:dodge-coronet/bonneville-salt-flats] "Speed Week" events in August were canceled in 2015 and 2022, due to the poor condition of the salt in certain parts of the flats.
[src:dodge-coronet/bonneville-salt-flats] The salt flats had been swamped by heavy rains earlier in the year, as usual, but this year the rains also triggered mudslides from surrounding mountains onto a section of the flats used for the land-speed racing courses.
[src:dodge-coronet/bonneville-salt-flats] In 2004, the *Stardust* spacecraft released its sample-return capsule for a landing in the Bonneville Salt Flats after its flybys of asteroid 5535 Annefrank in 2002 and comet Wild 2 in 2004.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] The **Dodge Coronet** is an automobile that was marketed by Dodge in seven generations, and shared nameplates with the same bodyshell with varying levels of equipment installed.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] Introduced as a full-size car in 1949, it was the division's highest trim line and moved to the lowest level starting in 1955 through 1959.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] The name was reintroduced on intermediate-sized models from the 1965 until 1976 model years.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] Muscle car versions were available starting in 1965 with the 383 and 426 wedge cu in (7.0 L) Chrysler RB engine, followed in 1966 by the powerful 426 cu in (7.0 L) Chrysler Hemi.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] Other performance models included the "Superbee", and featured, the 383 cu in (6.3 L) Magnum, among other engine options.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] The nameplate "coronet" is a type of crown worn by royalty.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] In the 1980s, the Coronet was used on Dodge models marketed in Colombia.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] The Dodge Coronet was introduced with the division's first postwar body styles.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] Lower trim lines were the Wayfarer and Meadowbrook, with the Wayfarer being built on a shorter 115 inch wheelbase.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] The only engine for Dodge was a 230-cubic-inch (3,800 cc) flat-head straight six cylinder engine with a single barrel Stromberg carburetor, producing 103 hp (77 kW) (gross).
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] The stock Dodge Coronet was a smooth-running car, and the six-cylinder engine could power the car to 90 mph (145 km/h).
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] A limited production model was a four-door, eight-passenger limousine, an extended version of the stock Dodge Coronet which was related to the DeSoto Suburban.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] One of the most notable features of the first-generation Coronet was Chrysler's four forward-speed, a fluid-driven semi-automatic transmission that Dodge Division called Gyromatic.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] After using the clutch and gear shift to select the high range, upshifts and downshifts were operated by the accelerator pedal on the floor.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] The clutch did not need to be depressed in stop-and-go driving once underway.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] It had full instrumentation and 37 inches of head room both front and rear.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] All Dodge vehicles received a facelift for 1950 but like the 1949 models were still divided into Wayfarer, Meadowbrook, and Coronet lines.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] The 1950 models can be identified easily by the new grille design which featured 3 heavy horizontal bars.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] The upper and lower bars formed a stylish oblong shape.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] Within this oblong grille was a thick center bar with parking lights on each end and a large chrome plaque in the center bearing the Dodge crest.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] Dodge received yet another facelift in 1951 but this time the cars remained virtually unchanged for two model years.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] Busy manufacturing military vehicles for use in Korea, they chose not to dedicate valuable resources to completely redesign civilian vehicles.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] Still divided into Wayfarer, Meadowbrook, and Coronet lines through 1952, by 1953 the Wayfarer line had been discontinued.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] The grille of the 1951 model was similar in shape to the 1950 grille, but with the elimination of the thick vertical center bar and the addition of six vents running horizontally between the top and center bars, a whole new look was achieved.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] The Coronet Diplomat was Dodge's first hardtop coupe, featuring a pillarless steel roof styled after the contemporary Chrysler Newport.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] The speedometer was now circular, and the other four gauges were rectangles.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] For 1952 the Coronet had a painted lower grille louver.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] For 1953, the Coronet was totally redesigned.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] It gained an optional 241 cu in (3.9 L) "Red Ram" Hemi Engine and set over 100 land speed records at the Bonneville Salt Flats.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] The windshield finally became one-piece.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] Electric windshield wipers were standard, while the radio cost $83.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] The Dodge Royal line was added above the Coronet in 1954.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] Dodge was putting more luxury into all of its models which included the Meadowbrook, Coronet and new Royal lines.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] Still, styling changes for 1954 were modest.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] The chrome molding on the hood lip was wider than on the 1953 models and a large chrome upright in the center of the grille replaced the five vertical dividers used previously.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] It still came with full instrumentation.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] 1954 saw Chrysler's first fully automatic transmission, two-speed PowerFlite, offered as an extra-cost option on all Dodges.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] The 1955 Coronet dropped to the lower end of the Dodge vehicle lineup, with the Wayfarer and Meadowbrook names no longer used and the Custom Royal added above the Royal, Lancer, and La Femme.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] Bodies were restyled with help from newly hired Virgil Exner to be lower, wider, and longer than the lumpy prewar style, which in turn generated a healthy boost in sales over 1954.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] Two V8 engines were offered: 270 cu in (4.4 L) Polyspheric (poly or semi-hemi) heads producing 175 hp (130 kW) and a 315 cu in (5.2 L) (the "Hemi").
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] Power windows were added to the available options.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] 1956 (*See also: Plymouth Fury*) was the last year of this body style before the change in 1957, the only differences offered in 1956 from the previous year were trim packages and the new Dodge D-500.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] The D-500 was the first Dodge factory high-performance production version as a tribute to the (D-500-1) "Super Stock" model.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] The only external clues were small crossed checkered flags and "500" lettering on its hood and lower rear deck.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] It was also available for order from the dealer on Coronet models, including station wagons and two-door sedans.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] The standard D-500 trim included a 315 cu in (5.2 L) V8 with hemispherical heads (unlike other Dodge V8s (List of Chrysler engines) which used Polyspheric heads), a unique camshaft, valve lifters, pushrods, carburetor, ignition, and pistons.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] With a compression ratio of 9.25:1, four-barrel Carter WCFB carburetor, and dual-point distribution, peak horsepower was 260 bhp (190 kW) while torque was a solid 330 lb⋅ft (450 N⋅m).
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] The D-500 also received an upgraded suspension with stiff front coil springs; heavy-duty Oriflow shock absorbers, with the same valving specified for Dodge police cars, were mounted in the springs.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] The overall height of the D-500 was 1.5 inches (38 mm) lower than its standard Dodge counterpart.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] The D-500 came standard with 15x5.5 inch wheels with 7.60x15 inch tubeless tires.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] The D-500-1 the first 500 made required by NASCAR, was intended for NASCAR competition.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] The D-500-1 had an even stiffer suspension than the D-500.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] Under the hood, the engine received larger valves (about 18% larger), a full-race camshaft, and a double log intake manifold that used two four-barrel Carter WCFB carburetors and a shaved deck for 8.25:1 compression.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] The 285 bhp (213 kW) meant it was the fastest car that year from the factory.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] The 1957 model year debuted a new D-501, which replaced the D-500 from the year before as the top Coronet.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] The D-501 received Chrysler's proven 354 cu in (5.8 L) Hemi V8, which were actually leftover engines from the 1956 Chrysler 300B production.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] Camshafts from the 1957 Chrysler 392 cu in (6.4 L) engines were installed in the 354 cu in (5.8 L) V8s.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] A pair of Carter four-barrel carburetors fed the 10.0:1 compression ratio to produce 340 bhp (250 kW), shared with the DeSoto Adventurer and the Chrysler 300C.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] Other changes included the addition of the Torsion-Aire Ride (torsion bar) front suspension and a heavy-duty suspension with heavy-duty shock absorbers and a heavy-duty leaf-sprung rear.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] A 3.73:1 rear axle was standard with the three-speed manual transmission and automatic cars included a 3.18:1 rear axle.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] There were 13 optional rear axles available, ranging from 2.92:1 through 6.17:1.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] Brakes were 12-inch (300 mm) diameter drums.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] In the September 1957 issue of *Popular Mechanics*, owners of both the Coronet six-cylinder and eight-cylinder were surveyed.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] Many (37.6% of I6 owners and 34.8% of V8 owners) complained that there were too many water leaks.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] When PM tested a V8 Coronet for water resistance, water got into the engine and pooled in "two spark plug wells" which had to be siphoned out before the engine could run with all cylinders again.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] However, many did like the exterior styling and the ride comfort.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] Acceleration from 0-60 mph on 90 octane gasoline was 12.3 seconds.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] The 1958 and 1959 Coronet, Royal, and Custom Royal used a DeSoto Fireflite chassis but had less ornate trim.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] Power came from the 230 cu in (3.8 L) "Getaway" L-head straight-6 or the 325 cu in (5.3 L) "Red Ram" V8.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] In 1959 a Silver Challenger model was also offered on the Coronet line.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] This was a six-cylinder or V-8 model available only in silver paint and only on a two-door body.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] It came with many extra features at no cost, such as wall-to-wall deep pile carpeting, premium white wall tires and wheel covers, luxury fabrics and upgraded interior and electric windshield wipers.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] The overall length was increased to 217.4 inches.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] A Dodge Coronet was the only known example of the JATO Rocket Car legend.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] To publicize Dodge's 'total contact' front dual-leading shoe drum brakes a JATO unit was fitted to a 1958 Coronet and driven at speed across the El Mirage dry lake.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] A TV advertisement was broadcast during Dodge-sponsored Lawrence Welk Show.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] The first car that carried the Challenger name was introduced as the limited edition *Dodge Silver Challenger* Club Sedan, an addition to the 1959 full-sized Dodge Coronet model line. and was related to the Dodge Matador.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] The Silver Challenger came only in silver paint and exclusively on Chrysler's 217.4 in (5,520 mm) long two-door, on a 122 in (3,100 mm) wheelbase.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] This car was marketed for the spring selling season to "new-car buyers who've been waiting to get the most for the least." A column-shifted three-speed manual transmission was standard and an automatic was optional.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] The 1959 Silver Challenger was marketed with extra features at no extra cost.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] These included premium white wall tires, full wheel covers, electric windshield wipers, as well as an upgraded interior with silver metallic vinyl and black "Manchu" fabric upholstery, dual arm rests and sun visors, as well as deep pile wall-to-wall carpeting.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] The Coronet reappeared for the 1965 model year as the intermediate-sized B-body using a 117-inch wheelbase, continuing what had been the Dodge Polara, which was once again full-size.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] For 1965, Dodge sold slightly over 209,000 units, making the Coronet the most popular model sold by Dodge that year.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] Trim levels initially were base Coronet, Coronet 440, and Coronet 500.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] The base Coronet was available as two-door sedans, four-door sedans, and station wagons.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] Front seat belts and padded dash were standard.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] The middle of the Coronet line-up was the 440 which was available as a two-door hardtop, convertible, or station wagon.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] The 440 designation did not indicate engine displacement as commonly assumed (both then and now, which helped sales to an extent).
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] The nomenclature was a carryover theme from the 1963–64 Polara series.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] The top of the Coronet line-up was the Coronet 500 which was available as a two-door hardtop or convertible in 1965.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] Slightly over 33,300 units were sold in 1965 and included as standard, a V8 engine (273 cubic inches), exterior trim and badging, bucket seats, padded dash, and chrome floor console.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] Coronets were manufactured at Chrysler's Los Angeles assembly plant, the Lynch Road assembly plant in Detroit, and the St.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] Engines offered for 1965 included the base 225 Slant-Six, and optional 273, 318, 361, 383, and 426 V8s, the latter available with either single or dual four-barrel carburetors.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] Sales brochures list the 413 (its last year offered) as available, but no records exist of this engine, commonly used in Imperials, being installed in Coronets for 1965.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] In 1966 a four-door Coronet 500 was added, called the Coronet 500 SE (Special Edition).
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] It had special "SE" logos on the C-pillars and on the seatback.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] There would be no Coronet 500 wagon until 1968.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] Coronet received a redesign in 1966, and a facelift in 1967.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] In 1966, the Coronet Deluxe was introduced, fitting between the base Coronet and the Coronet 440.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] The Coronet R/T was available as a two-door hardtop or convertible.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] The standard engine was Chrysler's largest, the 440 cu in (7.2 L) V8 producing 375 bhp and dubbed the Magnum.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] The only engine option was the 426-cid Hemi, now in its second year in "Street" trim and again rated at 425 bhp.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] Transmission choices were Mopar's excellent heavy-duty three-speed TorqueFlite automatic or a four-speed manual.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] When the 426ci Hemi was made available to the general public for the 1966 model year, it could be ordered in any Coronet model or trim level.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] No Hemi-powered Coronet wagons have been verified, but a few Coronet Deluxe four-door sedans are known to exist.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] A total of 136 Coronet 500 Street Hemis were built for 1966.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] Beginning in 1967, Chrysler decided that the Hemi should be available only in their badged muscle cars: the Dodge Charger, Coronet R/T, and the Plymouth Belvedere GTX.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] The top engine option for the rest of the Coronet line was supposed to be the 383-ci, 4-barrel V8.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] Despite this, some Hemi-powered 1967 Coronet Deluxe two-door sedans were produced.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] There is also one Hemi-powered 1967 Coronet 440 two-door hardtop known, and One Hemi-powered 1967 Coronet 500 two-door hardtop known, which is not among the 55 WO23 Super Stock cars produced for Dodge drag racers.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] The Coronet and similar Plymouth Belvedere received complete redesigns in 1968, as did the Dodge Charger, which shared the B-body platform.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] Trim levels initially included the base Coronet, Coronet Deluxe, Coronet 440, Coronet 500, and Coronet R/T.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] The Coronet Super Bee was introduced in early 1968 as a companion to the Plymouth Road Runner.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] In keeping with Dodge's position as a step above Plymouth, the Super Bee shared the Charger's Rallye instrument cluster and the Coronet 440's rear finish panel.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] As in 1967, the 440ci RB V8 was only available in the Coronet R/T in 1968.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] The 426ci Hemi V8 was supposed to be limited to the R/T and Super Bee, but two 1968 Coronet 440s are known to have been built with this engine.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] In mid-1969, the A12 package was introduced on the Super Bee.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] It included a 390 hp (291 kW) version of the 440 with three 2bbl Holley carburetors on an aluminum intake manifold, a black fiberglass lift-off hood secured with metal pins, heavy-duty suspension, and 15-inch steel wheels with no hubcaps or wheel covers.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] The A12 Super Bee could be had with most Super Bee options, with the exception of air conditioning and tire-wheel packages.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] The A12 option was a 1969-only package, but the 440 6bbl returned in 1970 as an optional engine on the Super Bee.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] This engine option was exclusive to the Super Bee and not available on any other Coronet.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] The base Coronet and Deluxe were available as 2-door coupes, 4-door sedans, or station wagons.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] The base Coronet was dropped in 1969, leaving the Deluxe as the lowest trim level through 1970.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] The Coronet 440 convertible was dropped for 1968, but a 2-door coupe was added along with the 2-door hardtop, 4-door sedan, and station wagon.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] This would remain the lineup through 1970.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] Coronet 500 retained its 2-door hardtop, convertible, and 4-door sedan through 1970.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] A Coronet 500 station wagon made its debut in 1968, continuing through 1970.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] Simulated woodgrain trim was standard on the Coronet 500 wagon.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] The Coronet R/T 2-door hardtop and convertible continued through 1970.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] The Super Bee was available as a 2-door coupe or 2-door hardtop.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] Chrysler displayed a convertible with Super Bee stripes at car shows in 1968, but never offered it as a production model.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] The Dodge Super Bee was a limited-production muscle car from 1968 through 1971.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] The original Super Bee was based on the Dodge Coronet, a 2-door model, and was produced from 1968 until 1970.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] It was Dodge's low-priced muscle car, the equivalent to Plymouth Road Runner, and was priced at $3,027.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] Available with the Hemi engine, this option increased the price by 33% thus 125 models were sold with this engine option.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] The Super Bee included a heavy-duty suspension, an optional Mopar A-833 four-speed manual transmission, high-performance tires, and a stripe (with the bee logo) wrapped around the tail.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] The name "Super Bee" was derived from the "B" Body designation given Chrysler's mid-size cars which included the Coronet.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] A “six-pack” (three two-barrel carburetors) version of the 440 engine was added to the list mid-year.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] This engine was between the standard engine and the Hemi as a $463 option.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] The 1969 model year included the base 383 hp (high performance) with the 440 six-pack and 426 Hemi optional.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] The 440 Magnum (4-bbl) was not available in the Coronet R/T.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] In 1970, the Super Bee was given a different front-end look that consisted of a dual oval-shaped grill that was referred to as “bumble bee wings”.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] Engines, as well as the "ramcharger" hood (that carried over from the 1969 model).
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] In 1970, four Super Bee convertibles were built.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] The new Coronet was a twin of the four-door Plymouth Satellite and featured more flowing styling.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] It was offered as a sedan and wagon, the related and also restyled Dodge Charger covering the coupe market.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] Slight alterations of the front grille, headlights, and taillights followed in 1972.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] In addition to the usual changes to the grille, lights, and interior, Dodge introduced in 1973 to mid-size models its "TorsionQuiet" system of additional silencers and rubber vibration insulators, providing a much smoother ride and a quieter interior.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] The front and rear fascias were redesigned, most notably the rear bumper, which met the 1974 DOT requirements.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] The sedan body style would be the basis of the later Coronets (and its twin, the Plymouth Fury) until the 1978 model year.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] For 1975 the Coronet received a refreshed squarer-appearing body as well as a new front fascia with two round dual-beam headlights shared with its Plymouth Fury stablemate.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] After a four model year absence, a Dodge Coronet 2-door returned for 1975.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] 1976 was the final model year for the Dodge Coronet and its body style choices were reduced to four-door wagon and four-door sedan.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] The former Dodge Coronet 2-door model was replaced by the Dodge Charger Sport for the 1976 model year.
[src:dodge-coronet/dodge-coronet] For the 1977 model year, the mid-size Dodge Coronet was renamed Monaco, and the full-size Dodge Monaco was renamed Royal Monaco.
